    <p><a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a></p>

    <h1>Con&#xAD;spir&#xAD;acy-thriller se&#xAD;ries star&#xAD;ing at con&#xAD;tro&#xAD;versy</h1>
    <h2>Given the Covid-19 cri&#xAD;sis, Utopia&#x2019;s sug&#xAD;ges&#xAD;tion that there is a con&#xAD;spir&#xAD;acy be&#xAD;hind its fic&#xAD;tional pan&#xAD;demic has led to flak that it may be fan&#xAD;ning the flames of con&#xAD;spir&#xAD;acy think&#xAD;ing</h2>
    <section>
        <time datetime="2021-01-12"><a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210112/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-12">2021-01-12</a></time> -
        Ali&#xAD;son de Souza stlife@sph.com.sg&#xD;&#xA;Utopia is avail&#xAD;able on Ama&#xAD;zon Prime Video.

            <a href="/category/tag-268435461/en/sg">Entertainment</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268449461/en/sg">Comics</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268449474/en/sg">Movies</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268490453/en/sg">Geek Culture</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268487377/en/sg">Utopia</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268450473/en/sg">Infectious Diseases</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268489617/en/sg">Social Sciences</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268489459/en/sg">Health Conditions</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537984056/en/sg">Gillian Flynn</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-540748731/en/sg">Amazon Prime</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-536892326/en/sg">Amazon</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-540281347/en/sg">Amazon Video</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537070026/en/sg">Bill Gates</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-538707699/en/sg">Gone Girl</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537069217/en/sg">Donald Trump</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537068240/en/sg">United States of America</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-537286254/en/sg">Washington</a> &middot;            <a href="/category/tag-268489870/en/sg">Philosophy</a>     </section>

        <p>The con­spir­acy-thriller se­ries Utopia was not try­ing to be pre­scient with its story – about a group of comic-book nerds hunt­ing down a graphic novel that warns of a pan­demic.</p>
        <p>But in the wake of the Covid-19 cri­sis, the show’s sug­ges­tion that there is a dark con­spir­acy be­hind its fic­tional pan­demic has led to crit­i­cism that it may be fan­ning the flames of con­spir­acy think­ing.</p>
        <p>At a vir­tual press con­fer­ence, showrun­ner and writer Gil­lian Flynn said pro­duc­tion on the sci­ence-fic­tion com­edy – stream­ing on Ama­zon Prime Video – was com­pleted be­fore the coro­n­avirus hit the news early last year.</p>
        <p>Adapted from the 2013 Bri­tish show of the same name, it fol­lows a group of young peo­ple who get swept up in a con­spir­acy af­ter ob­tain­ing a cult un­der­ground graphic novel they are ob­sessed with.</p>
        <p>Called Utopia, the comic ap­pears to proph­esy the de­lib­er­ate cre­ation of a flu-like ill­ness as part of a scheme to de­pop­u­late the planet.</p>
        <p>John Cu­sack (High Fidelity, 2000) plays Dr Kevin Christie, a Bill Gates-like fig­ure and pow­er­ful biotech­nol­ogy en­tre­pre­neur who is pro­mot­ing a vac­cine that will os­ten­si­bly pro­tect peo­ple from the virus. But he turns out to have ne­far­i­ous in­ten­tions.</p>
        <p>But any re­sem­blance to the Covid-19 sit­u­a­tion is a co­in­ci­dence, Flynn says.</p>
        <p>Still, the se­ries does end up ad­dress­ing some broader is­sues rel­e­vant to what is hap­pen­ing now, says the writer, who penned the best-sell­ing 2012 psy­cho­log­i­cal thriller Gone Girl as well as the 2014 movie adap­ta­tion.</p>
        <p>“We started and ended film­ing be­fore the real-life pan­demic hap­pened, but as far as the res­o­nance of what is truth, what’s re­al­ity and how much we be­lieve in in­sti­tu­tions – those were all in play as I started writ­ing it,” says the 49-year-old, who also wrote the psy­cho­log­i­cal thriller Sharp Ob­jects (2006).</p>
        <p>In more re­cent in­ter­views, how­ever, Flynn ad­mits that she has been “un­set­tled” by the sim­i­lar­i­ties be­tween her screen­play and what is hap­pen­ing – es­pe­cially in terms of con­spir­a­cies sur­round­ing the Covid-19 vac­cines.</p>
        <p>She has also clar­i­fied that she wrote the show be­fore she knew about QAnon, the dis­cred­ited far­right con­spir­acy the­ory favoured by some sup­port­ers of United</p>
        <p>States Pres­i­dent Don­ald Trump, in­clud­ing a few of those who stormed the Capi­tol build­ing in Wash­ing­ton DC re­cently.</p>
        <p>And while she did in­tend to ex­am­ine how con­spir­a­cies are born and gain mo­men­tum – even if they fly in the face of avail­able ev­i­dence – the fact that the plot of Utopia in­volves a harm­ful vac­cine was not in­tended as a dig at the Covid-19 vac­cines, Flynn said.</p>
        <p>“It is a story, at its core, about a group of comic-book nerds who are out to get Utopia be­cause they think it has dif­fer­ent an­swers to their prob­lems, some of which are very per­sonal.</p>
        <p>“Some of them are fight­ing this pan­demic that they be­lieve is pos­si­bly go­ing to change the end of the world.”</p>
        <p>And “it did feel like right now was ex­actly the time” for this story, she adds.</p>
        <p>Her i nspi­ra­tion for the dark comic tone of the show were “1970s con­spir­acy thrillers and para­noia thrillers” such as the po­lit­i­cal drama The Par­al­lax View (1974) and sus­pense thriller Marathon Man (1976).</p>
        <p>“In fact, when I was pitch­ing this, I called it The Goonies meets Marathon Man,” she says, re­fer­ring to the 1985 chil­dren’s ad­ven­ture com­edy.</p>
        <p>“And that was kind of the blue­print, this idea of a rag­tag group of un­likely he­roes who get caught in an in­cred­i­bly dark con­spir­acy. I wanted it to feel ragged and dirty and nasty.”</p>
        <p>Flynn has also found her­self hav­ing to de­fend the graphic vi­o­lence on the show, which kills off char­ac­ters at an im­pres­sive rate.</p>
        <p>“I am of­ten ‘less is more’ as far as vi­o­lence goes. I don’t want it for car­toon ef­fect or nec­es­sar­ily for shock value. I want to use vi­o­lence when it’s ef­fec­tive and when it’s ap­pro­pri­ate and cor­rect.”</p>
        <p>But, she says, her in­ten­tion here was for the au­di­ence “to be squirm­ing right along with the char­ac­ters”.</p>
        <p>“So that you do feel for th­ese char­ac­ters and un­der­stand that th­ese are real-life stakes.”</p>
        <p>Cu­sack, 54, says the point of the vi­o­lence is also to high­light the dif­fer­ence be­tween how comic­book and cos­play geeks “think of vi­o­lence in a comic-book way, ver­sus the con­trast when the story of the comic book comes to life”.</p>
        <p>“So, I don’t think it’s gra­tu­itous and, when it is violent, it’s with pur­pose.”</p>
        <p>I am of­ten ‘less is more’ as far as vi­o­lence goes. I don’t want it for car­toon ef­fect or nec­es­sar­ily for shock value. I want to use vi­o­lence when it’s ef­fec­tive and when it’s ap­pro­pri­ate and cor­rect.</p>
        <p>SHOWRUN­NER AND WRITER OF UTOPIA GIL­LIAN FLYNN (right), on the use of vi­o­lence in the sci­ence-fic­tion com­edy</p>

